+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| A New Way to Look at Networking                                    |
|   from the well-isn't-that-special dept.                           |
|   posted by CmdrTaco on Sunday May 06, @09:20 (The Internet)       |
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/06/1252210              |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]Van Jacobson gave a [1]Google Tech Talk on some of his ideas of how a
modern, global network could work more effectively, and with more trust
in the data which changes many hands on its journey to its final
destination. [1]Watch the talk on Google's site The man is very smart and
his ideas are fascinating. He has the experience and knowledge to see the
big picture and what can be done to solve some of the new problems we
have. He starts with the beginning of the phone networks and then goes on
to briefly explain the origins of the [2]ARPAnet and its evolution into
the Internet we use today. He explains the problems that were faced while
using the phone networks for data, and how they were solved by realizing
that a new problem had risen and needed a new, different solution. He
then goes to explain how the Internet has changed significantly from the
time it started off in research centres, schools, and government offices
into what it is today (lots of identical bytes being redundantly pushed
to many consumers, where broadcast would be more appropriate and
efficient).

Discuss this story at:
    http://slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/06/1252210

Links:
    0. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Van_Jacobson
    1. http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-6972678839686672840&hl=en
    2. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ARPANET


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| AOL's Embarassing Password Woes                                    |
|   from the top-sekrit dept.                                        |
|   posted by CmdrTaco on Sunday May 06, @10:26 (Security)           |
|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/06/1347214           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "AOL.com users may think they have up to
sixteen characters to use as a password, but they'd be wrong, thanks to
this [0]security artifact detailed by The Washington Post's Security Fix
blog: "Well, it turns out that when someone signs up for an AOL.com
account, the user appears to be allowed to enter up to a 16-character
password. AOL's system, however, doesn't read past the first eight
characters." This means that a user who uses "password123" or any other
obvious eight-character password with random numbers on the end is in
effect using just that lame eight-character password."

Discuss this story at:
    http://it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/06/1347214

Links:
    0. http://blog.washingtonpost.com/securityfix/2007/05/aols_password_puzzler.html


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Bill Gates' Management Style                                       |
|   from the behold-the-glorious-borg-icon dept.                     |
|   posted by CmdrTaco on Sunday May 06, @11:31 (Microsoft)          |
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/06/1423223              |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

replicant108 wrote in to give us Tom Evslin's [0]fascinating account of
working for Microsoft in the early 90s. "So you're in there presenting
your product plan to billg, steveb, and mikemap. Billg typically has his
eyes closed and he's rocking back and forth. He could be asleep; he could
be thinking about something else; he could be listening intently to
everything you're saying. The trouble is all are possible and you don't
know which. Obviously, you have to present as if he were listening
intently even though you know he isn't looking at the PowerPoint slides
you spent so much time on. At some point in your presentation billg will
say "that's the dumbest fucking idea I've heard since I've been at
Microsoft." He looks like he means it. However, since you knew he was
going to say this, you can't really let it faze you. Moreover, you can't
afford to look fazed; remember: he's a bully."

Discuss this story at:
    http://slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/06/1423223

Links:
    0. http://blog.tomevslin.com/2007/05/microsoft_memor.html


